{"parentUuid":"9a2a30e8-5c79-4a30-9780-892901132c24","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"56c1f686-0dd3-4bee-80a2-c7b716d4f5b3","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"ab8b315b200cb0bc4","slug":"shimmying-noodling-popcorn","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Wrkk3Pr2qkNoT7sjqrkJ7Y","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 900\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/900](https://www.erdosproblems.com/900)\n    23→\n    24→There exists a function $f$ with $f(c) \\to 0$ as $c \\to (1/2)^+$ and $f(c) \\to 1$ as\n    25→$c \\to \\infty$, such that for every $c > 1/2$, a random graph $G(n, \\lfloor cn \\rfloor)$\n    26→with high probability contains a path of length at least $f(c) \\cdot n$.\n    27→\n    28→[AKS81] Ajtai, M., Komlós, J. and Szemerédi, E., _The longest path in a random graph_,\n    29→Combinatorica 1 (1981), 1-12.\n    30→-/\n    31→\n    32→namespace Erdos900\n    33→\n    34→/-- A simple graph $G$ contains a path with at least $k$ edges, i.e., a sequence\n    35→of $k+1$ distinct vertices where consecutive vertices are adjacent. -/\n    36→def GraphHasLongPath {V : Type*} (G : SimpleGraph V) (k : ℕ) : Prop :=\n    37→  ∃ m : ℕ, m ≥ k ∧\n    38→    ∃ (path : Fin (m + 1) → V),\n    39→      Function.Injective path ∧\n    40→      ∀ i : ℕ, ∀ h : i < m,\n    41→        G.Adj (path ⟨i, by omega⟩) (path ⟨i + 1, by omega⟩)\n    42→\n    43→open Classical in\n    44→/-- The probability that a uniformly random simple graph on $\\operatorname{Fin}(n)$ with exactly\n    45→$m$ edges satisfies a given property, in the Erdős–Rényi $G(n,m)$ model.\n    46→This is the fraction $|\\{G \\in G(n,m) \\mid P(G)\\}| / |G(n,m)|$. -/\n    47→noncomputable def erdosRenyiProbability (n m : ℕ)\n    48→    (P : SimpleGraph (Fin n) → Prop) : ℝ :=\n    49→  let total := Finset.univ.filter (fun G : SimpleGraph (Fin n) => G.edgeFinset.card = m)\n    50→  ((total.filter (fun G => P G)).card : ℝ) / (total.card : ℝ)\n    51→\n    52→/--\n    53→Erdős Problem 900 (proved by Ajtai, Komlós, and Szemerédi [AKS81]):\n    54→\n    55→There exists $f : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}$ with $f(c) \\to 0$ as $c \\to (1/2)^+$ and\n    56→$f(c) \\to 1$ as $c \\to \\infty$, such that for every $c > 1/2$, a random graph\n    57→$G(n, \\lfloor cn \\rfloor)$ with high probability contains a path of length at least\n    58→$f(c) \\cdot n$.\n    59→-/\n    60→@[category research solved, AMS 5 60]\n    61→theorem erdos_900 :\n    62→    ∃ f : ℝ → ℝ,\n    63→    (Filter.Tendsto (fun h => f (1/2 + h))\n    64→      (nhdsWithin 0 (Set.Ioi 0)) (nhds 0)) ∧\n    65→    (Filter.Tendsto f Filter.atTop (nhds 1)) ∧\n    66→    (∀ c : ℝ, c > 1/2 → ∀ ε : ℝ, ε > 0 →\n    67→      ∃ N₀ : ℕ, ∀ n : ℕ, n ≥ N₀ →\n    68→        erdosRenyiProbability n (⌊c * (n : ℝ)⌋₊)\n    69→          (fun G => GraphHasLongPath G (⌊f c * (n : ℝ)⌋₊)) ≥ 1 - ε) := by\n    70→  sorry\n    71→\n    72→end Erdos900\n    73→"}]},"uuid":"07d488aa-8c6a-48ab-872c-6c1a45ccf82c","timestamp":"2026-03-11T05:34:07.435Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9a2a30e8-5c79-4a30-9780-892901132c24"}
{"parentUuid":"07d488aa-8c6a-48ab-872c-6c1a45ccf82c","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"56c1f686-0dd3-4bee-80a2-c7b716d4f5b3","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"ab8b315b200cb0bc4","slug":"shimmying-noodling-popcorn","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01K1rf1Tik4gYU3davjDwuky","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I found the Lean file for Erdos Problem 900. Here are the details:\n\n**File Path:** `/home/ryan/formal-conjectures/FormalConjectures/ErdosProblems/900.lean`\n\n**Contents:**\n\nThe file contains the formalization of Erdős Problem 900 in Lean. Here's a summary of what it includes:\n\n1. **Problem Statement**: There exists a function $f$ with $f(c) \\to 0$ as $c \\to (1/2)^+$ and $f(c) \\to 1$ as $c \\to \\infty$, such that for every $c > 1/2$, a random graph $G(n, \\lfloor cn \\rfloor)$ with high probability contains a path of length at least $f(c) \\cdot n$.\n\n2. **Key Definitions**:\n   - `GraphHasLongPath`: Defines when a simple graph contains a path with at least k edges\n   - `erdosRenyiProbability`: Computes the probability in the Erdős–Rényi G(n,m) model\n\n3. **Main Theorem** (`erdos_900`): Formalizes the complete problem statement with three conditions:\n   - The function $f$ approaches 0 as $c$ approaches $(1/2)^+$\n   - The function $f$ approaches 1 as $c$ approaches infinity\n   - For every $c > 1/2$, random graphs G(n, ⌊cn⌋) with high probability contain paths of length at least $f(c) \\cdot n$\n\nThe theorem is currently marked as sorry (incomplete proof) and is categorized with tags `[category research solved, AMS 5 60]`."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1626,"cache_read_input_tokens":19521,"output_tokens":419,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_